{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619814"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:37:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:37:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.06,0.64,0.17,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9274"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66043"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9274"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51500"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"2181"},{"type":"tags","id":"3320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"7102"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22080"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45767"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66043"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents with a three-week history of morning headaches, vomiting, and unsteady gait. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has bilateral papilloedema, truncal ataxia, and dysmetria on finger-nose testing. A magnetic resonance imaging scan of the brain is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely location of the lesion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior fossa","Middle fossa","Posterior fossa","Suprasellar region","Cerebral hemispheres"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents typical features of a posterior fossa tumour in a child, with symptoms of raised intracranial pressure (morning headaches, vomiting) and cerebellar dysfunction (ataxia, dysmetria). The clinical presentation and epidemiology strongly support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior fossa\u003C/strong\u003E tumours account for approximately 70% of all brain tumours in children over one year of age. Common types include medulloblastoma, cerebellar astrocytoma, and ependymoma. The confined space of the posterior fossa means these tumours often present with early signs of raised intracranial pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnterior fossa\u003C/strong\u003E tumours are relatively rare in children. When they do occur, they typically present with personality changes, anosmia, or visual disturbances rather than cerebellar signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMiddle fossa\u003C/strong\u003E tumours often present with seizures, temporal lobe symptoms, or cranial nerve palsies. These symptoms are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuprasellar region\u003C/strong\u003E tumours typically present with endocrine dysfunction and visual field defects due to their proximity to the pituitary gland and optic chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral hemisphere\u003C/strong\u003E tumours commonly present with focal neurological deficits, seizures, or personality changes, depending on their location. The presence of prominent cerebellar signs makes this location less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["70% of paediatric brain tumours in children over one year of age occur in the posterior fossa.","Common posterior fossa tumours in children include medulloblastoma, cerebellar astrocytoma, and ependymoma.","Posterior fossa tumours typically present with symptoms of raised intracranial pressure and cerebellar dysfunction."],"references":["Prasad KSV, Ravi D, Pallikonda V, Raman BVS. Clinicopathological Study of Pediatric Posterior Fossa Tumors. J Pediatr Neurosci. 2017 Jul-Sep;12(3):245-250. doi: 10.4103/jpn.JPN_113_16. PMID: 29204199; PMCID: PMC5696661.","Mengide JP, Berros MF, Turza ME, Li\u00f1ares JM. Posterior fossa tumors in children: An update and new concepts. Surg Neurol Int. 2023 Mar 31;14:114. doi: 10.25259/SNI_43_2023. PMID: 37151431; PMCID: PMC10159277.","Formentin C, Joaquim AF, Ghizoni E. Posterior fossa tumors in children: current insights. Eur J Pediatr. 2023 Nov;182(11):4833-4850. doi: 10.1007/s00431-023-05189-5. Epub 2023 Sep 8. PMID: 37679511.","Raybaud C, Ramaswamy V, Taylor MD, Laughlin S. Posterior fossa tumors in children: developmental anatomy and diagnostic imaging. Childs Nerv Syst. 2015 Oct;31(10):1661-76. doi: 10.1007/s00381-015-2834-z. Epub 2015 Sep 9. PMID: 26351220."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51500"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51500"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2